arXiv.title:
Anomalies in (semi)-leptonic $B$ decays $B^{\pm} 	o 	au^{\pm} 
u$, $B^{\pm} 	o D 	au^{\pm} 
u$ and $B^{\pm} 	o D^* 	au^{\pm} 
u$, and possible resolution with sterile neutrino

arXiv.abstract:
Recent works have associated systems of particles, characterized by short-range repulsive interactions and evolving under overdamped motion, to a nonlinear Fokker-Planck equation within the class of nonextensive statistical mechanics, with a nonlinear diffusion contribution whose exponent is given by $
u=2-q$. The particular case $
u=2$ applies to interacting vortices in type-II superconductors, whereas $
u>2$ covers systems of particles characterized by short-range power-law interactions, where correlations among particles are taken into account. In the former case, several studies presented a consistent thermodynamic framework based on the definition of an effective temperature $	heta$ (presenting experimental values much higher than typical room temperatures $T$, so that thermal noise could be neglected), conjugated to a generalized entropy $s_{
u}$ (with $
u=2$). Herein, the whole thermodynamic scheme is revisited and extended to systems of particles interacting repulsively, through short-ranged potentials, described by an entropy $s_{
u}$, with $
u>1$, covering the $
u=2$ (vortices in type-II superconductors) and $
u>2$ (short-range power-law interactions) physical examples. The main results achieved are: (a) The definition of an effective temperature $	heta$ conjugated to the entropy $s_{
u}$; (b) The construction of a Carnot cycle, whose efficiency is shown to be $\eta=1-(	heta_2/	heta_1)$, where $	heta_1$ and $	heta_2$ are the effective temperatures associated with two isothermal transformations, with $	heta_1>	heta_2$; (c) Thermodynamic potentials, Maxwell relations, and response functions. The present thermodynamic framework, for a system of interacting particles under the above-mentioned conditions, and associated to an entropy $s_{
u}$, with $
u>1$, certainly enlarges the possibility of experimental verifications.
